<div id="p540" class="blockpost roweven">
	<h2><span><span class="conr">#43&nbsp;</span><a href="viewtopic.php?pid=540#p540">2008-09-23 23:38:58</a></span></h2>
	<div class="box">
		<div class="inbox">
			<div class="postleft">
				<dl>
					<dt><strong><a href="profile.php?id=90050">shalunov</a></strong></dt>
					<dd class="usertitle"><strong>Member</strong></dd>
					<dd class="postavatar"></dd>
				</dl>
			</div>
			<div class="postright">
				<h3> Re: Discussion of BEP 15: UDP Tracker Protocol</h3>
				<div class="postmsg">
					<p>Bit saving concern appears overblown.&nbsp; I would not expect that cost of bits shipment is a measurable fraction of tracker operation costs.<br /><br />Server overhead and round-trip times could indeed be significantly decreased by using a UDP-based protocol.&nbsp; Examples of protocols that can handle vastly higher load than web servers per box are DNS and NTP.<br /><br />The BEP 15 protocol could be modified to further cut down on packet use and round-trip times by nearly a factor of two.&nbsp; This would also change the server memory use from O(#active connections) to O(1) and keep bit use about the same.<br /><br />Here's how:<br /><br />The server generates and stores in memory 128 or 256 pseudo-random bits used as a master key.&nbsp; The master key changes on every server restart.&nbsp; Old values are discarded when the server shuts down.<br /><br />Each client is responsible for obtaining and presenting tokens to the server.&nbsp; A client may store up to 1 token per server at a time.<br /><br />To obtain a token, a client sends the server a token request, which contains no information beyond just identifying the packet as a token request.&nbsp; The server responds by forming a message consisting of the client's IP number and authenticating this message using a HMAC with the master key as the key.&nbsp; The HMAC is the token.<br /><br />Clients need a token to talk to the server using any messages other than token request.&nbsp; They include the token in all requests.&nbsp; Should a token ever be rejected, they ask for a new one with exponential backoff.<br /><br />Timestamps are not necessary to make tokens expire -- just change the master key to effect that.<br /><br />This has the same security properties as random connection ids, but dramatically reduces memory use on the server while only very modestly increasing CPU use per request.&nbsp; Because tokens can survive for longer than connection ids, number of requests goes down.</p>
				</div>
			</div>
			<div class="clearer"></div>
			<div class="postfootleft"><p>Offline</p></div>
			<div class="postfootright"><div>&nbsp;</div></div>
		</div>
	</div>
</div>

